    <cas:Sofa xmi:id="1" sofaNum="1" sofaID="_InitialView" mimeType="text" sofaString="Multi-sectoral needs in Yobe were most commonly driven by needs for services in education (77%) and health (71%), and for food security support (66%). Health and education needs were the most common to co-occur, with 57% of Yobe households demonstrating dual need for services in these sectors. Education and food security were the second most common sectors in which needs co-occurred, with 54% of all Yobe households reporting simultaneous food security and education needs. A lack of available, formal education services was the dominant component of multi-sectoral needs and, of the 77% of households with unmet needs in the education sector, 46% registered a vulnerability, such as a high age-dependency ratio or a separated child. It is notable that Yobe reported the highest percentage of households hosting separated and unaccompanied children (6%) as compared to Borno (1%) and Adamawa (2%), which could contribute to higher education needs among school-aged children and vulnerabilities among households."/>
    <cas:View sofa="1" members="8 19 24 29 34 39 44 57 70 83 96 109 122 135 148 161 174 187 200 213 226 239 252 265 278 291 304 317 330 343 356 369 382 395 408 421 434 447 460 473 486 499 512 525 538 551 564 577 590 603 616 629 642 655 668 681 694 707 720 733 746 759 772 785 798 811 824 837 850 863 876 889 902 915 928 941 954 967 980 993 1006 1019 1032 1045 1058 1071 1084 1097 1110 1123 1136 1149 1162 1175 1188 1201 1214 1227 1240 1253 1266 1279 1292 1305 1318 1331 1344 1357 1370 1383 1396 1409 1422 1435 1448 1461 1474 1487 1500 1513 1526 1539 1552 1565 1578 1591 1604 1617 1630 1643 1656 1669 1682 1695 1708 1721 1734 1747 1760 1773 1786 1799 1812 1825 1838 1851 1864 1877 1890 1903 1916 1929 1942 1955 1968 1981 1994 2007 2020 2033 2046 2059 2072 2085 2098 2111 2124 2137 2150 2163 2176 2189 2202 2215 2228 2241 2254 2267 2280 2293 2306 2319 2332 2345 2358 2386 2391 2371 2376 2381 2424 2429 2441 2453 2458 2463 2482 2487 2499 2511 2516 2540 2545 2535 2550 2555 2417 2396 2403 2410 2434 2446 2468 2475 2492 2528 2504 2521 2567 2574 2588 2560 2581 2595 2602 2609 2612 2605 2616 2629"/>
